{"id":"1305.5005","submitter":"John Mahoney III","authors":"John R. Mahoney and Kevin A. Mitchell","title":"A turnstile mechanism for fronts propagating in fluid flows","comments":"16 pages, 24 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.4824675","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the propagation of fronts in a periodically driven flowing\nmedium. It is shown that the progress of fronts in these systems may be\nmediated by a turnstile mechanism akin to that found in chaotic advection. We\nfirst define the modified (\"active\") turnstile lobes according to the evolution\nof point sources across a transport boundary. We then show that the lobe\nboundaries may be constructed from stable and unstable \\emph{burning invariant\nmanifolds}---one-way barriers to front propagation analogous to traditional\ninvariant manifolds for passive advection. Because the burning invariant\nmanifolds (BIMs) are one-dimensional curves in a three-dimensional ($xy\\theta$)\nphase space, their projection into $xy$-space exhibits several key differences\nfrom their advective counterparts: (lobe) areas are not preserved, BIMs may\nself-intersect, and an intersection between stable and unstable BIMs does not\nmap to another such intersection. These differences must be accommodated in the\ncorrect construction of the new turnstile. As an application, we consider a\nlobe-based treatment protocol for protecting an ocean bay from an invading\nalgae bloom.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 22 May 2013 02:24:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-16"}
