{"id":"1306.3468","submitter":"M\\`arius Josep Fullana i Alfonso","authors":"Antonio Alfonso-Faus and M\\`arius Josep Fullana i Alfonso","title":"Cosmic Background Bose Condensation (CBBC)","comments":"14 pages. Accepted for publication in Astrophysics and Space Science.\n  arXiv admin note: substantial text overlap with arXiv:1212.1711","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s10509-013-1500-8","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Degeneracy effects for bosons are more important for smaller particle mass,\nsmaller temperature and higher number density. Bose condensation requires that\nparticles be in the same lowest energy quantum state. We propose a cosmic\nbackground Bose condensation, present everywhere, whith its particles having\nthe lowest quantum energy state, $\\hbar c / \\lambda$, with $\\lambda$ about the\nsize of the visible universe, and therefore unlocalized. This we identify with\nthe quantum of the self gravitational potential energy of any particle, and\nwith the bit of information of minimum energy. The entropy of the universe\n($\\sim 10^{122} \\ bits$) has the highest number density ($ \\sim 10^{36} \\ bits\n/ cm^3$) of particles inside the visible universe, the smallest mass, $\\sim\n10^{-66} g$, and the smallest temperature, $\\sim 10^{-29} K$. Therefore it is\nthe best candidate for a Cosmic Background Bose Condensation (CBBC), a\ncompletely calmed fluid, with no viscosity, in a superfluidity state, and\npossibly responsible for the expansion of the universe.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 21 May 2013 22:32:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-06-17"}
